@node INTRODUCTION UnTAR.guide/Introduction

@{line}@{u}@{b}Introduction@{ub}@{uu}@{par}

UnTAR is a small tool to extract files from so called
@{" tar " link GLOSSARY} archives. Such archives often have the extension
.tar, .tgz, .taz, or .tar.gz. A tar file can be compressed by by
@{" gzip " link GLOSSARY} (indicated by the "gz" or "z" in the
suffix).@{par}

Tar files can be seen as the Unix equivalent of lha or zip files: the
purpose is to store a number of files in a single file. By compressing the
entire tar file, good compression ratios can be achieved, but archive
processing is a bit clumsy: all operations require the entire archive to be
decompressed and possibly recompressed later.@{par}

The reason for writing UnTAR is that the programs tar and gzip are fairly
large, the Amiga versions keep the unix command line style and often
require @{" ixemul " link GLOSSARY}. UnTAR is written to be a simple,
compact, reasonably fast tar unpacker that use an Amiga-like command line
style.@{par}

@endnode



@node WHY "UnTAR.guide/Why UnTAR?"

@{line}@{u}@{b}Why UnTAR?@{ub}@{uu}@{par}

There are already several other programs with purposes similar to UnTAR, so
why write yet another one? Well, it all started because Oliver Wagner wrote
a program called UnTGZ (not related to UnTGZ by Andreas Kleinert). However,
it had a few problems. The latest version I'm aware of sometimes created
empty files when it should create files with contents. I wrote to Mr.
Wagner about it and also suggested a few improvements. However, I didn't
get any reply, nor did I see any updates. I considered making my own
version, but didn't know much about @{" tar " link GLOSSARY} files at the
time, so nothing happened.@{par}

Time passed. Then I saw the sources to a program called UnTGZ in the
@{" zlib " link GLOSSARY} distribution archive. It was a small and simple
.tgz-file unpacker and lister. I decided to make an Amiga version; it
turned out to be more a rewrite for the Amiga than a simple port (like
Andreas Kleinert's port mentioned above), and I added some new
features.@{par}

When UnTAR was almost finished, I looked at Aminet to see if there was any
program called UnTAR there already. I found a program called UnTAR and
several similar programs. I still felt that my program offered some
features the others didn't, so I decided to release it anyway. There were
already two programs called UnTGZ, so why not another UnTAR? ;)@{par}

@endnode




@node FEATURES UnTAR.guide/Features

@{line}@{u}@{b}Features@{ub}@{uu}@{par}

Small and simple to use program.@{par}

Modest system requirements. OS 2.04 is required for operation, OS 2.1+
features are used if available. About 100 kB of memory is needed to process
an archive.@{par}

Optionally prompts if files are about to be overwritten.@{par}

Uses AsyncIO for speed.@{par}

Includes a version optimized for a 68020 CPU or better.@{par}

Can be made resident.@{par}

Localized.@{par}

@endnode




@node USAGE UnTAR.guide/Usage

@{line}@{u}@{b}Usage@{ub}@{uu}@{par}

@{lindent 6}UnTAR [FILE] <File> [TO <Drawer>] [LIST] [KEEP] [NOPROMPT]
[QUIET] [CASE] [PATTERNS <Pattern> ...]@{par}@{lindent 0}

@{b}FILE@{ub}@{line}
Name of the @{" tar " link GLOSSARY} archive to process. This archive can
optionally be compressed by @{" gzip " link GLOSSARY}. UnTAR will
@{i}not @{ui}try to append any suffix if the specified file couldn't be
opened.@{par}

@{b}TO@{ub}@{line}
Specifies where the files in the archive should be extracted. This must
refer to an existing drawer.@{par}

This option is ignored if @{b}LIST@{ub} is specified.@{par}

@{b}LIST@{ub}@{line}
List the specified archive rather than extract the files in it. Note that
in this list, @{" protection bits " link GLOSSARY} and file names are shown
in Unix format rather than Amiga format, to faithfully display the archive
contents. The protection bits and file names are converted as needed when
extracted.@{par}

The summary at the bottom contains three numbers:@{line}
@{lindent 2}· Total size of the listed files.@{lindent 0}@{line}
@{lindent 2}· Number of bytes @{b}gained@{ub} through compression - if any - in percent
for the archive as a whole, not just the listed files.@{lindent 0}@{line}
@{lindent 2}· Number of files listed.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{b}KEEP@{ub}@{line}
By default, UnTAR will delete any files that it was unable to extract
completely. By specifying this option, partial files will not be
deleted.@{par}

This option is ignored if @{b}LIST@{ub} is specified.@{par}

@{b}NOPROMPT@{ub}@{line}
Do not show a prompt if a file to be extracted would overwrite an already
existing file; they will be silently overwritten. The prompt accepts four
answers: @{b}y@{ub} = yes, overwrite the file; @{b}n@{ub} = no, do not
overwrite the file; @{b}a@{ub} = all, overwrite the file and any further
files; @{b}s@{ub} = skip, do not overwrite the file nor any further files.
Any answer not matching the above is considered to be @{b}n@{ub}.@{par}

If there is no interactive input (i.e. there is no shell or similar to
accept input from) then no prompts will be showed and the default action is
to not overwrite any files. Use @{b}NOPROMPT@{ub} to make UnTAR overwrite
any existing files in this case.@{par}

This option is ignored if @{b}LIST@{ub} is specified.@{par}

@{b}QUIET@{ub}@{line}
While extracting, do not show messages about the files that are being
processed.@{par}

This option is ignored if @{b}LIST@{ub} is specified.@{par}

@{b}CASE@{ub}@{line}
Makes the patterns (see below) case sensitive. This is needed because on
Unix systems, file names are generally case sensitive, while on the Amiga
they are not. You can then use this option to extract files with the same
name but with different cases, should there be such files in the archive,
as UnTAR does not process these in any special way (due to the fact that
the OS does not care about the case of file names).@{par}

@{b}PATTERNS@{ub}@{line}
Any number of AmigaDOS patterns specifying which files in the archive to
process. This applies both to list and extract operations. Note that the
pattern matching is done on the names as shown by the @{b}LIST@{ub} option,
not the names of the created files. Most of the time these names are the
same.@{par}

@endnode




@node LIMITATIONS UnTAR.guide/Limitations

@{line}@{u}@{b}Limitations@{ub}@{uu}@{par}

Some of the limitations are due to lack of information on the tar archive
format and possible variations. Current behaviour is based on the sources
for untgz and GNU tar.@{par}

User and group ids for extracted files are ignored, as I'm not sure if they
can be supported in any useful way on the Amiga. Let me know what you
think.@{par}

Time zone handling isn't complete. If you have OS 2.1 or better, the
builtin Locale system will be used to find the GMT offset, but this does
not include daylight savings time. If you have OS 2.04, time zones are
ignored completely.@{par}

Links are ignored while extracting files. The main question is how they
should be handled. What if the link target comes later in the archive?
Should the links be soft or hard?@{par}

Some tar archives, and some files in some archives, will probably not work
with UnTAR. E.g., GNU extensions are not supported. Are they common?@{par}

File name handling might need improvements. Any leading "/"-char in the
file name is removed, and colons (":") are replaced with underscores ("_")
when files are extracted, but other chars might need to be taken care
of.@{par}

@endnode




