@node GLOSSARY UnTAR.guide/Glossary

@{line}@{u}@{b}Glossary@{ub}@{uu}@{par}

@{b}deflate@{ub}@{line}
Deflate is a common compression algorithm, e.g. used by zlib, gzip and
pkzip. It is a variation of LZ77, where the compressed data is further
compressed with huffman coding. Details can be found in rfc1951. The
algorithm can compress data quite well and reasonably fast.@{par}

@{b}gzip@{ub}@{line}
Gzip, short for GNU Zip, is a program that compresses single files using
the deflate algorithm.@{par}

@{b}ixemul@{ub}@{line}
ixemul is a shared Amiga library, written to make it easy to port Unix
programs to the Amiga. One problem, at least for small programs, is that
ixemul is quite large, around 150 kB.@{par}

@{b}tar@{ub}@{line}
Tar is an acronym for "@{b}t@{ub}ape @{b}ar@{ub}chive", and was designed
for storing backups on tapes. This means that the archive format as such
isn't the most efficient one, to simplify tape handling. However, by using
a program like gzip on a tar file, it becomes a compact way of storing
several files in one.@{par}

@{b}Unix protection bits@{ub}@{line}
These bits - sometimes called the file mode - consists of three groups of
three bits each. Each group contains @{u}r@{uu}ead, @{u}w@{uu}rite and
e@{u}x@{uu}ecute permissions for the file owner, users in the same group as
the owner and other users, in that order.@{par}

@{b}zlib@{ub}@{line}
zlib is a link library to compress (and uncompress) data using the deflate
algorithm.@{par}

@endnode




@node SOURCE UnTAR.guide/Source

@{line}@{u}@{b}Source@{ub}@{uu}@{par}

UnTAR.c is based on untgz.c, written by Pedro A. Aranda Gutďrrez and
adapted to Unix by Jean-loup Gailly. However, fairly large changes have
been made in order to make the Amiga version. Features have been added and
error handling have been improved a lot. Some information regarding
@{" tar " link GLOSSARY} files come from studies of the GNU tar
sources.@{par}

A part of @{" zlib " link GLOSSARY} (gzio.c) have been modified as well,
mainly to add AsyncIO support and remove code not needed by UnTAR. The
result is the file GZIO.c. Zlib as such was compiled without any changes
(note that uInt need to be set to a 32-bit int or long in zconf.h, or you
might get problems when compiling it with SAS/C 6.58 for a 68020+ CPU. I
noticed a strange bug in the peep-hole optimizer...).@{par}

Should anyone want to make a PowerPC version, please go ahead. I don't have
a PPC card myself, so it is a bit difficult for me to do. But please
contact me first, to avoid duplicated work.@{par}

@endnode




